ld to use it seems questionable. Plus, the instability of the source context path in CI could be problematic, especially since it isn't committed in the normal repo. Including a copy of the ASM source in the test project might be a solution.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Rethinking test modifications**\\n\\nI’m considering how to modify tests without duplicating the library source, which would be excessive with 26 files involved. Instead, I could use the existing dependency jar and adjust the bytecode to add line tables. I’m thinking about implementing this transformation in the build.gradle file using ASM, though it feels a bit challenging. I’m also contemplating improving the tests by covering the call sites but need to keep it simple. I wonder if changing the second missing test to public might help, but I realize that JUnit 5 doesn't require that. However, dynamic coverage isn’t showing correctly due to the report being generated before the current ClassReaderTest.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining build report discrepancies**\\n\\nI realized that the build report after the first attempt showed the constructor was covered, but the report might not be accurate. The user likely ran an external workflow that didn’t generate dynamic access coverage after my changes. It seems like the “newly covered none” could come from a system report rather than our local build. I wonder if the first test should have covered whether the algorithm could use the method, but it didn't. I might need to inform the user, but the task still expects code changes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating testing options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about creating a dedicated test file called `ClassReaderUnknownSourceTest`. I noted that dynamic access detection might only capture lines if the source file is included in coverage. The raw frame shows a null line, which seems problematic. I wonder if I can instruct `-H:DebugInfoSourceSearchPath` to help with Native Image tracking, but it looks like I can’t add a line table. Maybe Native Image can preserve source info, but not really. A JUnit test might confirm `ClassLoader.getSystemResourceAsStream`, yet the tracked frame concerns the test class. Should I consider updating the dynamic-access report? However, rules seem to prevent generating or modifying metadata or Native Image configuration. This is tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing line coverage issues**\\n\\nI'm considering if there's no line coverage, whether the source file could have complete coverage. But it looks like the frame line is null, which complicates things. I need to inspect the `parseStackFrame` regex, as \\\"Unknown Source\\\" matches but indicates no line coverage. If the raw frame were \\\"Unknown Source:0,\\\" then line mapping might work, but that's not possible. I could contemplate editing build logic to treat null lines as covered, but that feels like it could violate rules. The user wants to improve test coverage for an active dynamic-access class. They’re asking for focus there, so I need to be cautious with changes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring build.gradle workarounds**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to implement a workaround in `build.gradle` that injects a fake line for \\\"Unknown Source\\\" after generating the Jacoco report. That feels like a bad idea, though. I wonder if I could configure `generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport`, but it doesn't seem relevant in the test project. Maybe the CI is calculating \\\"newly covered call sites\\\" based on runtime dynamic-access output instead of the coverage report? It seems like it reports remaining metrics after previous dynamic-access evaluations, possibly measuring \\\"callsite executed\\\" by tests in Native.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_OZ43BJJalqFSgLNSqnWiOsf6|fc_039294fa729767480169fb8d0785108194b3a38c4dc44408a7", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/asm/asm/3.1/sr